What is a Planet?


  • The IAU definition of a planet: 
                  A planet is a celestial body that: 

  • orbits the Sun
  • has enough self-gravity & mass to be in
    hydrostatic equilibrium
  • has cleared the neighborhood around
    its orbit

Discovered Planets


  • First planet discovered around a pulsar in 1991

  • First planet discovered around a star in 1995

Techniques in Finding Planets


  • Doppler Velocimetry
  • Transit Photometry 
  • Microlensing 
  • Direct Imaging 

                  Here we will talk about only the first two techniques

Doppler Velocimetry


Also known as Radial Velocity Technique




RAdial Velocity Technique









The RV technique depends on 

  • mass of the star 
  • mass of the planet 
  • geometry 

Radial velocity technique


Doppler Effect 


Radial velocity Technique


What do we see? 


Radial velocity Technique


What do we get? 

If the mass of the host star is known
we get the minimum mass of the planet 

Orbital period can be determined 

Planet-Star distance can be estimated

Transit photometry


Transit of Venus 


Transit Photometry

Transit Photometry 


Real Observed Data 

Transit Photometry

What do we get? 

If the radius of the host star is known
we find the radius of the planet 

Inclination of the system can be determined 

Planet's atmospheric composition can 
also be determined 

Combining the Two techniques


What do we get? 

  • Planet mass and radius 
  • Orbital period 
  • Planet distance 
  • Planet composition 
  • Inclination angle 
  • Planetary system (if detectable)

Search for Habitable 
Planets 


What is Habitability? 

  • Stable Star 
  • Rocky Surface
  • Liquid Water 
  • Oxygen + Nitrogen
  • Adequate ambient temperature
  • Protection from UV

Search for habitable planets

The Habitable Zone 


M stars show promise because:

  • Have a long life 
  • HZ is closer to the star
  • Low mass <=> easier detection 
  • There are more of them

Conclusion

  • Two most successful techniques, RV and transit photometry have discovered the bulk of 770 planets we know

  • We are most likely to find planets by studying the property of stars 

  • With advancement in technology, Earth-like planets will be discovered in a decade
